#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Generate 365 technical cognitive science facts"""

facts = []

# Brain regions and anatomy (Days 1-100)
brain_regions = [
    ("Prefrontal Cortex Executive Functions", "The dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) in Brodmann areas 9 and 46 is crucial for working memory maintenance, with sustained firing of pyramidal neurons during delay periods. Damage to this region causes deficits in planning, cognitive flexibility, and goal-directed behavior.", "Goldman-Rakic, P. S. (1995). Architecture of the prefrontal cortex and the central executive."),
    ("Hippocampal Memory Formation", "The hippocampus, located in the medial temporal lobe, contains CA1, CA2, CA3, and dentate gyrus subfields. Long-term potentiation (LTP) in CA1 pyramidal cells, mediated by NMDA receptors, is the primary cellular mechanism for declarative memory encoding.", "Bliss, T. V., & Collingridge, G. L. (1993). A synaptic model of memory: long-term potentiation in the hippocampus."),
    ("Amygdala Fear Processing", "The basolateral amygdala (BLA) receives sensory input from the thalamus and cortex, while the central nucleus (CeA) projects to brainstem regions controlling autonomic responses. Fear conditioning activates protein kinase A (PKA) pathways in BLA neurons, strengthening synaptic connections.", "LeDoux, J. E. (2000). Emotion circuits in the brain."),
    ("Cerebellar Motor Learning", "The cerebellum contains over 50% of the brain's neurons despite being only 10% of its volume. Purkinje cells receive input from climbing fibers (error signals) and parallel fibers (context), with long-term depression (LTD) at parallel fiber-Purkinje cell synapses enabling motor learning.", "Ito, M. (2001). Cerebellar long-term depression: characterization, signal transduction, and functional roles."),
    ("Thalamic Relay Functions", "The thalamus acts as a relay station, with specific nuclei like the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) for vision and medial geniculate nucleus (MGN) for audition. Thalamocortical projections maintain topographic maps and gate sensory information flow to the cortex.", "Sherman, S. M., & Guillery, R. W. (2001). Exploring the thalamus and its role in cortical function."),
    ("Basal Ganglia Action Selection", "The striatum (caudate and putamen) receives cortical input and projects to the globus pallidus and substantia nigra. Dopamine from the substantia nigra pars compacta modulates striatal activity, with D1 receptors facilitating 'go' pathways and D2 receptors inhibiting 'no-go' pathways.", "Graybiel, A. M. (2005). The basal ganglia: learning new tricks and loving it."),
    ("Insular Cortex Interoception", "The anterior insula integrates interoceptive signals from the body with emotional and cognitive states. Functional MRI studies show insular activation during empathy, disgust, and awareness of heartbeat, suggesting its role in embodied cognition.", "Craig, A. D. (2009). How do you feel—now? The anterior insula and human awareness."),
    ("Anterior Cingulate Cortex Conflict Monitoring", "The dorsal anterior cingulate cortex (dACC) monitors response conflicts and errors. Event-related potentials show error-related negativity (ERN) originating from dACC when actions conflict with goals, triggering cognitive control adjustments.", "Botvinick, M. M., et al. (2001). Conflict monitoring and cognitive control."),
    ("Posterior Parietal Cortex Spatial Attention", "The intraparietal sulcus (IPS) contains neurons that encode spatial locations and shift attention. Lesions cause hemispatial neglect, where patients ignore the contralateral visual field, demonstrating the critical role in attention allocation.", "Corbetta, M., & Shulman, G. L. (2002). Control of goal-directed and stimulus-driven attention in the brain."),
    ("Temporal Pole Social Cognition", "The temporal pole (Brodmann area 38) is part of the extended social brain network. It integrates semantic knowledge with emotional and social context, with damage causing deficits in recognizing social situations and understanding others' mental states.", "Olson, I. R., et al. (2007). The enigmatic temporal pole: a review of findings on social and emotional processing."),
    ("Orbitofrontal Cortex Value Representation", "The orbitofrontal cortex (OFC) encodes stimulus value and expected outcomes. Neurons in OFC track reward prediction errors, updating value representations when outcomes differ from expectations, crucial for adaptive decision-making.", "Padoa-Schioppa, C., & Assad, J. A. (2006). Neurons in the orbitofrontal cortex encode economic value."),
    ("Ventral Tegmental Area Dopamine Release", "The VTA contains dopaminergic neurons that project to the nucleus accumbens (mesolimbic pathway) and prefrontal cortex (mesocortical pathway). Phasic dopamine release encodes reward prediction errors, with increased firing for unexpected rewards and decreased firing for omitted expected rewards.", "Schultz, W. (1998). Predictive reward signal of dopamine neurons."),
    ("Nucleus Accumbens Reward Processing", "The nucleus accumbens (NAcc) receives dopaminergic input from the VTA and glutamatergic input from the hippocampus, amygdala, and prefrontal cortex. Medium spiny neurons in the NAcc integrate these signals to drive motivated behavior and reinforcement learning.", "Sesack, S. R., & Grace, A. A. (2010). Cortico-Basal Ganglia reward network: microcircuitry."),
    ("Hypothalamus Homeostatic Regulation", "The hypothalamus contains distinct nuclei regulating different functions: the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) controls circadian rhythms via light input from the retina, while the arcuate nucleus regulates hunger through neuropeptide Y (NPY) and pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC) neurons.", "Saper, C. B., et al. (2005). The hypothalamic integrator for circadian rhythms."),
    ("Reticular Formation Arousal", "The brainstem reticular formation contains cholinergic and noradrenergic neurons that project diffusely to the cortex. The ascending reticular activating system (ARAS) maintains wakefulness, with lesions causing coma, demonstrating its critical role in consciousness.", "Moruzzi, G., & Magoun, H. W. (1949). Brain stem reticular formation and activation of the EEG."),
    ("Superior Colliculus Visual Attention", "The superior colliculus in the midbrain contains a retinotopic map and controls saccadic eye movements. Neurons fire before saccades to specific locations, with the buildup of activity representing the salience map for attention and eye movement planning.", "Krauzlis, R. J., et al. (2013). Superior colliculus and visual spatial attention."),
    ("Inferior Colliculus Auditory Processing", "The inferior colliculus in the midbrain integrates auditory information from both ears, processing binaural cues for sound localization. Neurons are tuned to interaural time differences (ITD) and interaural level differences (ILD), enabling spatial hearing.", "Grothe, B., et al. (2010). Mechanisms of sound localization in mammals."),
    ("Entorhinal Cortex Grid Cells", "The entorhinal cortex contains grid cells that fire at multiple locations forming a hexagonal grid pattern. These cells, along with place cells in the hippocampus, form the neural basis of spatial navigation and cognitive maps.", "Moser, E. I., et al. (2008). Place cells, grid cells, and the brain's spatial representation system."),
    ("Perirhinal Cortex Object Recognition", "The perirhinal cortex in the medial temporal lobe is critical for object recognition memory. Neurons show decreased firing (repetition suppression) when objects are repeated, reflecting familiarity signals that distinguish novel from familiar stimuli.", "Brown, M. W., & Aggleton, J. P. (2001). Recognition memory: what are the roles of the perirhinal cortex and hippocampus?"),
    ("Parahippocampal Cortex Scene Processing", "The parahippocampal place area (PPA) in the parahippocampal cortex shows selective activation for scenes and spatial layouts. Functional MRI reveals stronger responses to scenes than objects, supporting its role in processing spatial context and environmental layout.", "Epstein, R., & Kanwisher, N. (1998). A cortical representation of the local visual environment."),
    ("Fusiform Face Area", "The fusiform face area (FFA) in the fusiform gyrus shows selective activation for faces. Functional MRI and single-unit recordings reveal face-selective neurons that respond more strongly to faces than other objects, with some cells tuned to specific facial features.", "Kanwisher, N., et al. (1997). The fusiform face area: a module in human extrastriate cortex specialized for face perception."),
    ("Extrastriate Body Area", "The extrastriate body area (EBA) in the lateral occipitotemporal cortex responds selectively to images of human bodies and body parts. This region processes body form and posture, with activation correlating with body perception tasks.", "Downing, P. E., et al. (2001). A cortical area selective for visual processing of the human body."),
    ("Primary Visual Cortex V1", "Area V1 in the occipital lobe contains orientation-selective neurons organized in columns. Hubel and Wiesel's work revealed simple cells responding to edges at specific orientations and complex cells responding to movement, forming the foundation of visual processing.", "Hubel, D. H., & Wiesel, T. N. (1962). Receptive fields, binocular interaction and functional architecture in the cat's visual cortex."),
    ("Primary Auditory Cortex A1", "The primary auditory cortex in Heschl's gyrus contains tonotopic maps where neurons are organized by frequency preference. Different regions process different aspects of sound: core areas for basic features, belt areas for complex sounds, and parabelt areas for auditory object recognition.", "Kaas, J. H., & Hackett, T. A. (2000). Subdivisions of auditory cortex and processing streams in primates."),
    ("Primary Motor Cortex M1", "The primary motor cortex in the precentral gyrus contains a motor homunculus with larger representations for body parts requiring fine control. Pyramidal neurons in layer V project to the spinal cord, with firing rates encoding movement direction and force.", "Georgopoulos, A. P., et al. (1986). Neuronal population coding of movement direction."),
    ("Premotor Cortex Action Planning", "The premotor cortex (Brodmann area 6) is active during action planning and observation. Mirror neurons in this region fire both when performing an action and when observing others perform it, suggesting a role in action understanding and imitation.", "Rizzolatti, G., & Craighero, L. (2004). The mirror-neuron system."),
    ("Supplementary Motor Area", "The supplementary motor area (SMA) is involved in internally generated movements and motor sequences. Lesions cause akinesia and difficulty initiating movements, while stimulation produces complex movements, indicating its role in motor program selection.", "Tanji, J. (1994). The supplementary motor area in the cerebral cortex."),
    ("Broca's Area Language Production", "Broca's area (Brodmann areas 44 and 45) in the left inferior frontal gyrus is critical for speech production. Damage causes Broca's aphasia with non-fluent speech, agrammatism, and difficulty with syntax, while functional imaging shows activation during language production tasks.", "Grodzinsky, Y. (2000). The neurology of syntax: language use without Broca's area."),
    ("Wernicke's Area Language Comprehension", "Wernicke's area (Brodmann area 22) in the left superior temporal gyrus is essential for language comprehension. Lesions cause Wernicke's aphasia with fluent but meaningless speech and poor comprehension, demonstrating the separation of production and comprehension systems.", "Dronkers, N. F., et al. (2007). Paul Broca's historic cases: high resolution MR imaging of the brains of Leborgne and Lelong."),
    ("Angular Gyrus Reading", "The angular gyrus at the junction of temporal, parietal, and occipital lobes integrates visual, auditory, and somatosensory information. It's critical for reading, with damage causing alexia and agraphia, and shows activation during semantic processing and number operations.", "Dehaene, S., et al. (2010). How learning to read changes the cortical networks for vision and language."),
    ("Supramarginal Gyrus Phonological Processing", "The supramarginal gyrus in the inferior parietal lobule is involved in phonological processing and working memory for sounds. Functional imaging shows activation during rhyming tasks and phonological awareness, with damage affecting reading and spelling abilities.", "Paulesu, E., et al. (1996). Is developmental dyslexia a disconnection syndrome? Evidence from PET scanning."),
    ("Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex Working Memory", "The DLPFC maintains information in working memory through persistent neural activity. Delay-period firing of pyramidal neurons represents remembered information, with different neurons coding for different items, enabling the temporary storage needed for complex cognition.", "Funahashi, S., et al. (1989). Mnemonic coding of visual space in the monkey's dorsolateral prefrontal cortex."),
    ("Ventrolateral Prefrontal Cortex Response Inhibition", "The VLPFC, particularly the inferior frontal gyrus, is crucial for response inhibition. The stop-signal task reveals activation when subjects must cancel a planned response, with transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) disrupting this region impairing inhibitory control.", "Aron, A. R., et al. (2004). Inhibition and the right inferior frontal cortex."),
    ("Medial Prefrontal Cortex Self-Referential Processing", "The medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC) shows increased activation during self-referential thinking and theory of mind tasks. Default mode network activity in this region is higher during rest than during tasks, suggesting its role in internal mentation.", "Gusnard, D. A., et al. (2001). Medial prefrontal cortex and self-referential mental activity."),
    ("Posterior Cingulate Cortex Default Mode", "The posterior cingulate cortex (PCC) is a hub of the default mode network, showing high metabolic activity at rest. It's involved in autobiographical memory retrieval, future thinking, and self-projection, with decreased activity during externally focused tasks.", "Raichle, M. E., et al. (2001). A default mode of brain function."),
    ("Precuneus Consciousness", "The precuneus in the medial parietal cortex shows the highest metabolic rate in the brain. It's involved in self-awareness, episodic memory retrieval, and consciousness, with lesions causing deficits in self-consciousness and autobiographical memory.", "Cavanna, A. E., & Trimble, M. R. (2006). The precuneus: a review of its functional anatomy and behavioural correlates."),
    ("Superior Temporal Sulcus Biological Motion", "The superior temporal sulcus (STS) processes biological motion and social cues. Point-light displays of human movement activate this region, and it responds to eye gaze direction, facial expressions, and goal-directed actions, making it crucial for social perception.", "Allison, T., et al. (2000). Social perception from visual cues: role of the STS region."),
    ("Temporoparietal Junction Theory of Mind", "The temporoparietal junction (TPJ) is activated during theory of mind tasks requiring understanding others' mental states. Functional imaging shows increased activity when subjects think about others' beliefs, intentions, and perspectives, distinct from self-referential processing.", "Saxe, R., & Kanwisher, N. (2003). People thinking about thinking people: the role of the temporo-parietal junction in 'theory of mind'."),
    ("Inferior Temporal Cortex Object Recognition", "The inferior temporal cortex contains neurons selective for complex visual objects. These neurons show invariant responses across changes in position, size, and lighting, with hierarchical processing from simple features to complex object representations.", "Logothetis, N. K., & Sheinberg, D. L. (1996). Visual object recognition."),
    ("Lateral Occipital Complex", "The lateral occipital complex (LOC) processes object shape and structure. Functional MRI shows activation for objects versus scrambled versions, with stronger responses to intact objects, supporting its role in shape perception and object recognition.", "Malach, R., et al. (1995). Object-related activity revealed by functional magnetic resonance imaging in human occipital cortex."),
    ("Middle Temporal Area Motion Processing", "Area MT (V5) in the middle temporal cortex is specialized for motion perception. Neurons are direction-selective, responding to movement in specific directions, with lesions causing motion blindness (akinetopsia) where the world appears as a series of static frames.", "Zeki, S., et al. (1991). A direct demonstration of functional specialization in human visual cortex."),
    ("Ventral Intraparietal Area Multisensory Integration", "The ventral intraparietal area (VIP) integrates visual, auditory, and somatosensory information in peripersonal space. Neurons respond to stimuli near the body from multiple modalities, creating a multisensory representation of space around the individual.", "Duhamel, J. R., et al. (1998). Ventral intraparietal area of the macaque: congruent visual and somatic response properties."),
    ("Lateral Intraparietal Area Attention", "The lateral intraparietal area (LIP) contains a salience map for attention and eye movements. Neurons show increased firing for attended locations and before saccades to those locations, with activity representing the priority of different spatial locations.", "Bisley, J. W., & Goldberg, M. E. (2010). Attention, intention, and priority in the parietal lobe."),
    ("Frontal Eye Fields Saccade Control", "The frontal eye fields (FEF) in the premotor cortex control voluntary saccades. Electrical stimulation produces eye movements, and neurons fire before saccades to specific locations, with activity representing the target of upcoming eye movements.", "Bruce, C. J., & Goldberg, M. E. (1985). Primate frontal eye fields. I. Single neurons discharging before saccades."),
    ("Cingulate Motor Areas", "The cingulate motor areas (CMA) in the cingulate sulcus are involved in internally generated movements and action selection. These areas project to the spinal cord and show activation during voluntary movements, pain processing, and emotional responses to actions.", "Picard, N., & Strick, P. L. (1996). Motor areas of the medial wall: a review of their location and functional activation."),
    ("Rostral Cingulate Zone Error Detection", "The rostral cingulate zone (RCZ) monitors performance and detects errors. Event-related potentials show error-related negativity (ERN) and error positivity (Pe) originating from this region when subjects make mistakes, triggering performance adjustments.", "Ridderinkhof, K. R., et al. (2004). The role of the medial frontal cortex in cognitive control."),
    ("Subgenual Anterior Cingulate Depression", "The subgenual anterior cingulate cortex (sgACC) shows abnormal activity in depression, with increased glucose metabolism in treatment-resistant cases. Deep brain stimulation of this region can alleviate depression symptoms, suggesting its role in mood regulation.", "Mayberg, H. S., et al. (2005). Deep brain stimulation for treatment-resistant depression."),
    ("Retrosplenial Cortex Navigation", "The retrosplenial cortex connects the hippocampus with parietal and visual areas, playing a crucial role in spatial navigation. Lesions cause topographical disorientation, and functional imaging shows activation during navigation tasks and spatial memory retrieval.", "Vann, S. D., et al. (2009). The retrosplenial cortex and cognition: a review of functional studies."),
    ("Parahippocampal Gyrus Context", "The parahippocampal gyrus processes spatial context and scene information. The parahippocampal place area (PPA) shows stronger responses to scenes than objects, with activation correlating with memory for contextual details of events.", "Aminoff, E., et al. (2013). The parahippocampal cortex mediates spatial and nonspatial associations."),
    ("Subiculum Memory Output", "The subiculum is the main output structure of the hippocampus, receiving input from CA1 and projecting to cortical and subcortical areas. It's involved in spatial memory and navigation, with place cells showing location-specific firing patterns.", "O'Mara, S. M., et al. (2009). The subiculum: a review of form, physiology and function."),
    ("Dentate Gyrus Pattern Separation", "The dentate gyrus performs pattern separation, creating distinct representations of similar inputs. Adult neurogenesis in the dentate gyrus produces new granule cells that integrate into circuits, with these new neurons showing enhanced plasticity and contributing to memory discrimination.", "Aimone, J. B., et al. (2011). Resolving new memories: a critical look at the dentate gyrus, adult neurogenesis, and pattern separation."),
    ("CA3 Autoassociative Memory", "CA3 contains extensive recurrent connections enabling autoassociative memory. These connections allow pattern completion, where partial cues can retrieve complete memories, with long-term potentiation strengthening connections between co-active neurons.", "Marr, D. (1971). Simple memory: a theory for archicortex."),
    ("CA1 Memory Consolidation", "CA1 receives input from CA3 via Schaffer collaterals and projects to the subiculum and entorhinal cortex. Long-term potentiation in CA1, dependent on NMDA receptors and protein synthesis, is crucial for memory consolidation and retrieval.", "Nakazawa, K., et al. (2004). NMDA receptors, place cells and hippocampal spatial memory."),
    ("Entorhinal Cortex Layer II Grid Cells", "Layer II of the entorhinal cortex contains stellate cells that function as grid cells, firing at multiple locations forming hexagonal grids. These cells provide spatial input to the hippocampus, with grid scale increasing along the dorsoventral axis.", "Hafting, T., et al. (2005). Microstructure of a spatial map in the entorhinal cortex."),
    ("Entorhinal Cortex Layer III", "Layer III of the entorhinal cortex contains pyramidal cells that project to CA1. These cells show conjunctive coding of position and head direction, integrating spatial and directional information for navigation and memory.", "Sargolini, F., et al. (2006). Conjunctive representation of position, direction, and velocity in entorhinal cortex."),
    ("Perirhinal Cortex Familiarity", "The perirhinal cortex shows decreased firing (repetition suppression) for familiar objects, signaling recognition memory. This region is critical for object recognition, with lesions causing severe deficits in discriminating novel from familiar objects.", "Brown, M. W., & Aggleton, J. P. (2001). Recognition memory: what are the roles of the perirhinal cortex and hippocampus?"),
    ("Postrhinal Cortex Spatial Processing", "The postrhinal cortex (homologous to parahippocampal cortex in primates) processes spatial and contextual information. It connects visual areas with the hippocampus and shows activation during spatial navigation and context-dependent memory tasks.", "Burwell, R. D., & Amaral, D. G. (1998). Cortical afferents of the perirhinal, postrhinal, and entorhinal cortices of the rat."),
    ("Presubiculum Head Direction", "The presubiculum contains head direction cells that fire when the head points in a specific direction. These cells integrate vestibular and visual information to maintain a sense of orientation, crucial for spatial navigation.", "Taube, J. S. (2007). The head direction signal: origins and sensory-motor integration."),
    ("Parasubiculum Spatial Processing", "The parasubiculum processes spatial information and connects with the entorhinal cortex and subiculum. It contains neurons that respond to spatial location and boundaries, contributing to the spatial representation system.", "Boccara, C. N., et al. (2010). Grid cells in pre- and parasubiculum."),
    ("Subiculum Place Cells", "The subiculum contains place cells that fire at specific locations, similar to hippocampal place cells. These cells show less precise firing fields than CA1 place cells but provide important output for spatial navigation and memory.", "Sharp, P. E. (1999). Complimentary roles for hippocampal versus subicular/entorhinal place cells in coding place, context, and events."),
    ("Fornix Memory Pathways", "The fornix is the major output pathway of the hippocampus, carrying axons from CA3 and subiculum to the mammillary bodies and other subcortical structures. Lesions of the fornix cause memory deficits, demonstrating its critical role in memory circuits.", "Aggleton, J. P., & Brown, M. W. (1999). Episodic memory, amnesia, and the hippocampal-anterior thalamic axis."),
    ("Mammillary Bodies Memory", "The mammillary bodies receive input from the fornix and project to the anterior thalamus. They're part of the Papez circuit for memory, with lesions causing amnesia and Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome affecting this structure.", "Vann, S. D., & Aggleton, J. P. (2004). The mammillary bodies: two memory systems in one?"),
    ("Anterior Thalamic Nuclei", "The anterior thalamic nuclei receive input from the mammillary bodies and project to the cingulate cortex. They're part of the memory circuit, with lesions causing amnesia and functional imaging showing activation during memory tasks.", "Aggleton, J. P., & Brown, M. W. (1999). Episodic memory, amnesia, and the hippocampal-anterior thalamic axis."),
    ("Mediodorsal Thalamus Prefrontal Connections", "The mediodorsal thalamus (MD) has reciprocal connections with the prefrontal cortex. Lesions cause executive function deficits similar to prefrontal damage, suggesting it's crucial for maintaining prefrontal function and working memory.", "Mitchell, A. S., et al. (2012). Advances in understanding mechanisms of thalamic relays in cognition and behavior."),
    ("Pulvinar Attention", "The pulvinar nucleus of the thalamus modulates attention and visual processing. It connects with visual and parietal cortices, with lesions causing visual neglect and functional imaging showing activation during attention tasks.", "Petersen, S. E., et al. (1987). The pulvinar and visual salience."),
    ("Lateral Geniculate Nucleus Vision", "The lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN) relays visual information from the retina to V1. It contains magnocellular (motion) and parvocellular (color, detail) pathways, with layers receiving input from different eyes, maintaining retinotopic organization.", "Hubel, D. H., & Wiesel, T. N. (1961). Integrative action in the cat's lateral geniculate body."),
    ("Medial Geniculate Nucleus Audition", "The medial geniculate nucleus (MGN) relays auditory information from the inferior colliculus to the auditory cortex. It contains tonotopic organization and processes binaural cues for sound localization, with different subdivisions processing different aspects of sound.", "Winer, J. A., & Schreiner, C. E. (2011). The medial geniculate body: the thalamic relay for auditory information."),
    ("Ventral Posterior Nucleus Somatosensation", "The ventral posterior nucleus (VP) relays somatosensory information from the body to the somatosensory cortex. It maintains somatotopic organization (body map), with different regions representing different body parts, and processes touch, pain, and proprioception.", "Mountcastle, V. B. (2005). The sensory hand: neural mechanisms of somatic sensation."),
    ("Reticular Nucleus Thalamic Inhibition", "The reticular nucleus of the thalamus contains GABAergic neurons that inhibit thalamic relay nuclei. It acts as a gate, controlling information flow to the cortex, with activity modulating sleep-wake states and attention.", "Steriade, M., et al. (1997). The reticular thalamic nucleus: structure, function and concept."),
    ("Subthalamic Nucleus Movement", "The subthalamic nucleus (STN) is part of the indirect pathway of the basal ganglia, inhibiting movement. Deep brain stimulation of the STN alleviates Parkinson's disease symptoms, with neurons showing increased firing in movement disorders.", "Benabid, A. L., et al. (2009). Deep brain stimulation of the subthalamic nucleus for the treatment of Parkinson's disease."),
    ("Globus Pallidus Output", "The globus pallidus (GP) is the main output structure of the basal ganglia, with the internal segment (GPi) inhibiting the thalamus. Increased GPi activity in Parkinson's disease causes movement difficulties, with deep brain stimulation reducing this inhibition.", "DeLong, M. R. (1990). Primate models of movement disorders of basal ganglia origin."),
    ("Substantia Nigra Pars Compacta Dopamine", "The substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc) contains dopaminergic neurons projecting to the striatum. Loss of these neurons in Parkinson's disease causes motor symptoms, with dopamine modulating striatal activity through D1 and D2 receptors.", "Olanow, C. W., & Tatton, W. G. (1999). Etiology and pathogenesis of Parkinson's disease."),
    ("Substantia Nigra Pars Reticulata GABA", "The substantia nigra pars reticulata (SNr) contains GABAergic neurons that inhibit the thalamus and superior colliculus. It's part of the basal ganglia output, with activity controlling movement initiation and eye movements.", "Hikosaka, O., et al. (2000). Role of the basal ganglia in the control of purposive saccadic eye movements."),
    ("Red Nucleus Motor Control", "The red nucleus in the midbrain is involved in motor control, particularly for the upper limbs. It receives input from the cerebellum and motor cortex, with the rubrospinal tract controlling fine motor movements.", "Massion, J. (1988). Red nucleus: past and future."),
    ("Periaqueductal Gray Pain Modulation", "The periaqueductal gray (PAG) in the midbrain modulates pain through descending pathways. Stimulation produces analgesia, with different columns controlling different aspects of pain and defensive behavior.", "Bandler, R., & Shipley, M. T. (1994). Columnar organization in the midbrain periaqueductal gray: modules for emotional expression?"),
    ("Locus Coeruleus Norepinephrine", "The locus coeruleus (LC) in the pons is the main source of norepinephrine in the brain. LC neurons fire during arousal and attention, with phasic firing enhancing signal processing and tonic firing promoting exploration.", "Aston-Jones, G., & Cohen, J. D. (2005). An integrative theory of locus coeruleus-norepinephrine function: adaptive gain and optimal performance."),
    ("Raphe Nuclei Serotonin", "The raphe nuclei in the brainstem are the main source of serotonin (5-HT) in the brain. Different nuclei project to different regions, with the dorsal raphe involved in mood and the median raphe in memory and sleep.", "Jacobs, B. L., & Azmitia, E. C. (1992). Structure and function of the brain serotonin system."),
    ("Pedunculopontine Nucleus Arousal", "The pedunculopontine nucleus (PPN) in the brainstem contains cholinergic neurons involved in arousal and REM sleep. It's part of the ascending reticular activating system, with deep brain stimulation showing promise for treating sleep disorders.", "Garcia-Rill, E., et al. (2013). The pedunculopontine nucleus and REM sleep."),
    ("Nucleus Basalis Acetylcholine", "The nucleus basalis of Meynert provides cholinergic input to the cortex. Loss of these neurons in Alzheimer's disease contributes to cognitive decline, with acetylcholine crucial for attention, learning, and memory.", "Bartus, R. T., et al. (1982). The cholinergic hypothesis of geriatric memory dysfunction."),
    ("Medial Septum Hippocampal Theta", "The medial septum provides cholinergic and GABAergic input to the hippocampus, generating theta rhythms (4-8 Hz). Theta oscillations are associated with memory encoding and spatial navigation, with septal lesions disrupting these rhythms and memory.", "Buzsáki, G. (2002). Theta oscillations in the hippocampus."),
    ("Diagonal Band of Broca", "The diagonal band of Broca provides cholinergic input to the hippocampus and olfactory bulb. It's part of the basal forebrain cholinergic system, with neurons showing activity related to attention and memory processes.", "Mesulam, M. M., et al. (1983). Central cholinergic pathways in the rat: an overview based on an alternative nomenclature."),
    ("Bed Nucleus of the Stria Terminalis Stress", "The bed nucleus of the stria terminalis (BNST) processes anxiety and stress responses. It receives input from the amygdala and projects to hypothalamic and brainstem regions, with different subregions controlling different aspects of stress responses.", "Walker, D. L., et al. (2003). The role of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis versus the amygdala in fear, stress, and anxiety."),
    ("Nucleus Accumbens Core and Shell", "The nucleus accumbens has core and shell subdivisions with different functions. The core is involved in goal-directed behavior and learning, while the shell processes reward and motivation, with different connectivity patterns supporting these roles.", "Zahm, D. S., & Brog, J. S. (1992). On the significance of subterritories in the 'accumbens' part of the rat ventral striatum."),
    ("Ventral Pallidum Reward", "The ventral pallidum receives input from the nucleus accumbens and is involved in reward processing. It contains GABAergic neurons that project to the thalamus and brainstem, with activity encoding reward value and motivation.", "Smith, K. S., et al. (2009). Ventral pallidum roles in reward and motivation."),
    ("Lateral Habenula Aversion", "The lateral habenula encodes negative outcomes and aversive signals. It inhibits dopaminergic neurons in the VTA and SNc when outcomes are worse than expected, with increased activity in depression and addiction.", "Matsumoto, M., & Hikosaka, O. (2009). Representation of negative motivational value in the primate lateral habenula."),
    ("Medial Habenula", "The medial habenula processes aversive information and stress. It receives input from the septum and projects to the interpeduncular nucleus, with cholinergic neurons involved in stress responses and aversive learning.", "Hsu, Y. W., et al. (2013). Role of the dorsal medial habenula in the regulation of voluntary activity."),
    ("Interpeduncular Nucleus", "The interpeduncular nucleus receives input from the medial habenula and is involved in stress and anxiety responses. It contains cholinergic and GABAergic neurons that modulate brainstem and midbrain activity.", "Lecourtier, L., & Kelly, P. H. (2007). A conductor hidden in the orchestra? Role of the habenular complex in monoamine transmission and cognition."),
    ("Area Postrema Chemoreception", "The area postrema in the brainstem lacks a blood-brain barrier and detects toxins in the blood. It triggers vomiting and conditioned taste aversion, with neurons responding to circulating substances that indicate poisoning.", "Borison, H. L. (1989). Area postrema: chemoreceptor circumventricular organ of the medulla oblongata."),
    ("Nucleus of the Solitary Tract", "The nucleus of the solitary tract (NTS) receives visceral sensory input from the vagus nerve. It processes taste, gastrointestinal, and cardiovascular information, with different subnuclei processing different modalities and projecting to various brain regions.", "Travers, S. P., & Travers, J. B. (2006). Taste and visceral afferent pathways converge onto common brainstem targets."),
    ("Dorsal Motor Nucleus of the Vagus", "The dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus (DMV) contains preganglionic parasympathetic neurons controlling the gut. It receives input from the NTS and hypothalamus, with activity regulating digestive functions and gut-brain communication.", "Rogers, R. C., et al. (1996). Vagal afferent stimulation-evoked gastric secretion suppressed by paraventricular nucleus lesion."),
    ("Nucleus Ambiguus", "The nucleus ambiguus contains motor neurons controlling the larynx, pharynx, and esophagus. It's involved in swallowing, speech, and vocalization, with different subnuclei controlling different muscles and functions.", "Bieger, D., & Hopkins, D. A. (1987). Viscerotopic representation of the upper alimentary tract in the medulla oblongata in the rat: the nucleus ambiguus."),
    ("Hypoglossal Nucleus Tongue Control", "The hypoglossal nucleus contains motor neurons controlling tongue movements. It receives input from the cortex and brainstem, with activity essential for speech, swallowing, and tongue protrusion.", "Lowe, A. A. (1981). The neural regulation of tongue movements."),
    ("Facial Nucleus Expression", "The facial nucleus contains motor neurons controlling facial muscles. It receives input from the motor cortex and brainstem, with different subnuclei controlling different facial muscles, enabling facial expressions and communication.", "Jenny, A. B., & Saper, C. B. (1987). Organization of the facial nucleus and corticofacial projection in the monkey: a reconsideration of the upper motor neuron facial palsy."),
    ("Trigeminal Motor Nucleus", "The trigeminal motor nucleus contains motor neurons controlling jaw muscles. It receives input from the cortex and brainstem, with activity controlling chewing, biting, and jaw movements essential for feeding.", "Lund, J. P. (1991). Mastication and its control by the brain stem."),
    ("Oculomotor Nucleus Eye Movements", "The oculomotor nucleus contains motor neurons controlling eye muscles. It receives input from the superior colliculus and frontal eye fields, with activity controlling vertical and horizontal eye movements and pupil constriction.", "Leigh, R. J., & Zee, D. S. (2015). The neurology of eye movements."),
    ("Trochlear Nucleus", "The trochlear nucleus contains motor neurons controlling the superior oblique eye muscle. It's the only cranial nerve that decussates (crosses), with lesions causing vertical diplopia and difficulty looking down and in.", "Buttner-Ennever, J. A. (2006). The extraocular motor nuclei: organization and functional neuroanatomy."),
    ("Abducens Nucleus", "The abducens nucleus contains motor neurons controlling the lateral rectus eye muscle. It receives input from the paramedian pontine reticular formation (PPRF) for horizontal saccades, with lesions causing horizontal gaze palsy.", "Leigh, R. J., & Zee, D. S. (2015). The neurology of eye movements."),
    ("Vestibular Nuclei Balance", "The vestibular nuclei process information from the vestibular system about head position and movement. They control balance, eye movements (vestibulo-ocular reflex), and posture, with different nuclei processing different aspects of vestibular information.", "Angelaki, D. E., & Cullen, K. E. (2008). Vestibular system: the many facets of a multimodal sense."),
    ("Cochlear Nuclei Hearing", "The cochlear nuclei are the first central processing stations for auditory information. They receive input from the auditory nerve and process sound frequency, intensity, and timing, with different subdivisions processing different aspects of sound.", "Oertel, D., et al. (2002). The ascending auditory pathway: structure and function."),
    ("Superior Olivary Complex Sound Localization", "The superior olivary complex (SOC) processes binaural cues for sound localization. The medial superior olive (MSO) processes interaural time differences (ITD) for low frequencies, while the lateral superior olive (LSO) processes interaural level differences (ILD) for high frequencies.", "Grothe, B., et al. (2010). Mechanisms of sound localization in mammals."),
    ("Inferior Colliculus Auditory Integration", "The inferior colliculus integrates auditory information from both ears and lower brainstem nuclei. It processes sound location, frequency, and temporal patterns, with different subdivisions processing different aspects of auditory information before sending it to the thalamus.", "Casseday, J. H., et al. (2002). The inferior colliculus: a hub for the central auditory system."),
    ("Medial Geniculate Body Thalamic Relay", "The medial geniculate body (MGB) relays auditory information from the inferior colliculus to the auditory cortex. It contains tonotopic organization and processes different aspects of sound in different subdivisions, with the ventral division processing basic features and the dorsal division processing complex sounds.", "Winer, J. A., & Schreiner, C. E. (2011). The medial geniculate body: the thalamic relay for auditory information."),
    ("Primary Auditory Cortex Tonotopy", "The primary auditory cortex (A1) contains tonotopic maps where neurons are organized by frequency preference. Different regions process different aspects of sound, with core areas (A1, R, RT) processing basic features and belt areas processing complex sounds.", "Kaas, J. H., & Hackett, T. A. (2000). Subdivisions of auditory cortex and processing streams in primates."),
    ("Secondary Auditory Cortex", "The secondary auditory cortex (A2) processes more complex auditory features than A1. It shows less precise tonotopy and responds to complex sounds, with neurons tuned to specific features like frequency modulation and sound patterns.", "Rauschecker, J. P., & Tian, B. (2000). Mechanisms and streams for processing of 'what' and 'where' in auditory cortex."),
    ("Auditory Belt Areas", "The auditory belt areas surround the core auditory cortex and process complex sounds. They show less precise tonotopy and respond to auditory objects, with different regions processing different aspects of complex auditory information.", "Kaas, J. H., & Hackett, T. A. (2000). Subdivisions of auditory cortex and processing streams in primates."),
    ("Auditory Parabelt Areas", "The auditory parabelt areas process the most complex auditory information. They integrate auditory with other sensory information and are involved in auditory object recognition and speech processing, with connections to language and memory areas.", "Rauschecker, J. P., & Scott, S. K. (2009). Maps and streams in the auditory cortex: nonhuman primates illuminate human speech processing."),
    ("Planum Temporale Language", "The planum temporale in the superior temporal gyrus shows left-right asymmetry, with the left side larger in most people. This asymmetry is associated with language lateralization, with the left planum temporale involved in speech perception and processing.", "Geschwind, N., & Levitsky, W. (1968). Human brain: left-right asymmetries in temporal speech region."),
    ("Heschl's Gyrus Primary Auditory", "Heschl's gyrus contains the primary auditory cortex (A1) and shows individual variation in size and number. Functional imaging reveals tonotopic organization, with anterior regions processing low frequencies and posterior regions processing high frequencies.", "Da Costa, S., et al. (2011). Human primary auditory cortex follows the shape of Heschl's gyrus."),
    ("Superior Temporal Gyrus Auditory Objects", "The superior temporal gyrus (STG) processes complex auditory objects including speech and music. Different regions respond to different aspects of sound, with anterior regions processing speech and posterior regions processing spatial aspects of sound.", "Rauschecker, J. P., & Scott, S. K. (2009). Maps and streams in the auditory cortex: nonhuman primates illuminate human speech processing."),
    ("Auditory-Visual Integration", "The superior temporal sulcus (STS) integrates auditory and visual information. Neurons respond to both auditory and visual stimuli, with some showing enhanced responses when both modalities are present, supporting multisensory integration for speech and communication.", "Calvert, G. A., et al. (2000). Evidence from functional magnetic resonance imaging of crossmodal binding in the human heteromodal cortex."),
]

